title: "SP-PoR: Improve blockchain performance by semi-parallel processing transactions"
year: 2024
main_author: "Kaiyu Wang, Guangsheng Feng, Zhenzhou Ji, Zhiying Tu, and Shufan He"
main_contribution: "Semi-Parallel Proof-of-Relevance (SP-PoR) protocol that improves blockchain throughput by utilizing a compact Relation Certification (RC) structure to determine transaction relevance, allowing unrelated blocks to be processed in parallel while maintaining a linear order for related ones."
evidence_type: "Research Article"
technical_constraints: "Shortening block generation intervals or expanding capacity is ineffective due to network propagation latency; experimental throughput improvements of 8.575x for normal transactions and 2.54x for contract transactions; performance advantage depends on the execution proportion parameter ($\sigma < 0.462$)."
reference: "Wang, K., Feng, G., Ji, Z., Tu, Z., & He, S. (2024). SP-PoR: Improve blockchain performance by semi-parallel processing transactions. Computer Networks, 245, 110394."
doi: "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.comnet.2024.110394"
---

### SP-PoR: Improve blockchain performance by semi-parallel processing transactions

**Findings:**
- **Event Sourcing**: The source defines blockchain technology as a robust network infrastructure characterized by **tamper-proofing, traceability, and decentralization**. While not explicitly using the term "Event Sourcing," it describes an architecture where **every transaction—whether a normal transfer or a smart contract invocation—is recorded as an immutable event** that can be tracked back to its origin. This functionality provides the foundation for **auditability**, as the distributed ledger ensures that any attempt to modify or delete published information is irrefutably recorded and permanently stored.
- **High-Throughput (DAG/Chain)**: The authors identify that traditional **linear blockchain structures**, where each block has only one preceding block, suffer from limited processing capabilities due to network propagation latency. To achieve higher throughput, the source proposes a **multi-way tree Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) and a tangle structure** that allow for the generation and processing of multiple concurrent blocks. A significant trade-off is that while parallel processing of **unrelated blocks** (those with no shared accounts or dependencies) does not affect consensus achievement, **related blocks must be processed in a deterministic linear order** to prevent permanent forks or double-spending.
- **Consistency (ACID)**: Consistency is maintained through the consensus protocol, which ensures that all honest nodes achieve **agreement on the final state of the shared ledger**. To manage high-concurrency updates, the system requires **consistency of users' local views** for any related ordered block pair, forcing a deterministic execution sequence for transactions that might conflict. The protocol employs an **epoch-based system**—defined as the interval between adjacent confirmed contract blocks—to coordinate updates and ensure a single, consistent version of the global state across the network.
- **Self-Repair/Integrity**: Integrity is enforced through **cryptographic tamper-proofing and digital signatures** that verify transaction ownership. A practical mechanism for automated auditing and self-repair is the **Relation Certification (RC)**, a compact data structure (only 23–33% of a full block) that allows nodes to **rapidly determine transaction relevance and verify block validity** without waiting for the full block broadcast. The system also utilizes a **cross-verification consensus method** where normal and contract blocks are nested via parent hashes to form a tangle; if a fork occurs, the **longest-chain mechanism** is used to ensure the network eventually converges on the honest branch.
- **Other Relevant Implementation Details**: The SP-PoR protocol utilizes **two distinct relevance determination paradigms**: $D_I$ for normal transfers based on input/output accounts, and $D_{II}$ for smart contracts, which accounts for **internal state space and contract invocation logic**. The research identifies an **advantage boundary** using the execution proportion parameter ($\sigma$); the proposed parallel synchronization method outperforms parallel execution methods when the **time spent on block execution is less than 46.2%** of the total consensus cycle.
```

