title: "Shard-DAG: A scalable and secure block-DAG sharding scheme for AI-driven 6G networks"
year: 2025
main_author: "Yongkai Fan, Wenyuan Zhang, Guodong Wu, Le Zhang, Chengnian Long, Gang Tan, and Neal N. Xiong"
main_contribution: "The development of Shard-DAG, a decentralized security architecture that integrates Block-DAG structures within a sharded network to enable parallel block processing, near-linear scalability, and robust defense against double-spending attacks."
evidence_type: "Research Article"
technical_constraints: "Network of 1,200 nodes with 8 shards; 102 ms average end-to-end delay; fault tolerance requires $n \ge 3f+1$ for inter-shard PBFT and $n \ge 2f+1$ for sharded environments; throughput improvements peak at 14.64x over traditional blockchain."
reference: "Fan, Y., Zhang, W., Wu, G., Zhang, L., Long, C., Tan, G., & Xiong, N. N. (2025). Shard-DAG: A scalable and secure block-DAG sharding scheme for AI-driven 6G networks. Digital Communications and Networks, 11, 1738–1750."
doi: "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dcan.2025.04.005"
---

### Shard-DAG: A scalable and secure block-DAG sharding scheme for AI-driven 6G networks

**Findings:**
- **Event Sourcing**: The source defines blockchain as a **decentralized, tamper-resistant foundation** that facilitates distributed trust management while ensuring data integrity and confidentiality. While not explicitly using the term "Event Sourcing," it describes an architecture where every transaction is an **immutable record** stored in a distributed ledger. For auditability, the system ensures that any attempt to modify or delete published information is **irrefutably recorded and permanently stored**, providing a reliable trust mechanism for edge nodes and terminal devices.
- **High-Throughput (DAG/Chain)**: The paper identifies that traditional **linear chain structures** are limited by "orphan blocks"—valid blocks that are discarded because they do not belong to the longest chain. In contrast, a **Block-DAG structure** accepts all valid concurrent blocks, enabling parallel block processing and significantly improving system scalability. Shard-DAG integrates these two concepts by adopting a Block-DAG structure **within each shard** to overcome the performance bottlenecks of traditional sharded blockchains. Experimental results show that Shard-DAG achieves **peak throughput improvements of 14.64 times** over traditional blockchains and **8.61 times** over standalone Block-DAG architectures.
- **Consistency (ACID)**: The sources address consistency by reintroducing sequentiality into the non-linear DAG structure through a **transaction sorting mechanism**. This mechanism provides a structured approach to block ordering that is essential for defending against double-spending attacks and ensuring **transaction order consistency**. To maintain consistency across shards, Shard-DAG utilizes a **"black box" interaction model** where only the ordered outputs of each shard are visible to others, reducing the complexity and synchronization overhead of cross-shard communication.
- **Self-Repair/Integrity**: Integrity is fundamentally maintained through **cryptographic hash functions** and the decentralized nature of the architecture, which mitigates centralized performance bottlenecks. A practical mechanism for automated auditing and self-repair is the **sorting consensus mechanism**, which has high fault tolerance; blocks that are delayed by network disruptions are eventually incorporated into the DAG to maintain **global consistency**. To ensure long-term inter-shard security, the system employs **periodic and random reconfiguration of shard memberships**, which prevents long-term collusion and makes single-shard takeover attacks significantly more difficult.
- **Other Relevant Implementation Details**: The architecture employs four distinct sharding strategies: **network sharding** (clustering nodes), **transaction sharding** (assigning tasks based on the first $k$ bits of addresses), **computation sharding**, and **storage (state) sharding** (storing only a portion of the global state). The system also features a **black-box mode** that allows it to remain compatible with existing sharding tools and engines by exposing a linear sequence of transactions to external users while maintaining a DAG internally.
```